Initially, 10 g of Pithecellobium dulce fruit peel was gathered from its indigenous location in Shirpur (Dhule, Maharashtra). Subsequently, the peel was cleansed with purified water. Following that, the temperature was adjusted to 60 °C to desiccate the peel in a laboratory oven and then cooled down to 40 °C gradually at a rate of −0.14 °C/min over 4 h. Initially, the peel was carefully sectioned into small fragments using a grinder. Subsequently, these fragments were finely ground to obtain a powdered peel. The synthesis of Co/N-GQDs was then performed using a one-step hydrothermal technique using Pithecellobium dulce fruit peel, Co (NO3)2, and urea (
                           Fig. 1

                           ). To elucidate this, 2 g of finely powdered Pithecellobium dulce fruit peel was mixed with 30 mL of DDW and subjected to 45 min of sonication. This resulting dispersion was combined with 200 mg of Co (NO3)2 and 100 mg of urea. Subsequently, the resultant mixture was transferred to a stainless steel hydrothermal reactor equipped with a Teflon-lined chamber. The hydrothermal reaction was executed in a hot air oven, maintaining a temperature of 180 °C for 10 h [33]. Subsequently, the reactor was allowed to cool naturally to reach room temperature. Next, the reaction mixture was transferred to a glass container and subjected to a 20-min ultrasonication process, followed by cooling to room temperature. Subsequently, any insoluble residues were effectively eliminated by filtering the solution through a microporous membrane with a pore size of 0.22 μm. The resulting golden amber solution was subjected to a 24-h dialysis procedure using a dialysis bag. Finally, the dialyzed solution was dried on a hot plate set at approximately 60 °C, yielding the dried product. This product was then collected, and the remaining solution was preserved at 8 °C for subsequent analysis.
